## Example 5 — Real-World Proof

An engineer needs to verify that two structural support beams (\(\overline{PR}\) and \(\overline{QS}\)) are equal in length. The supports form triangles with a shared horizontal beam, and measurements show:

* \(\overline{PQ} \cong \overline{RS}\) (equal horizontal segments)
* \(\angle P \cong \angle R\) (each support meets the horizontal beam at the same angle)
* \(\angle Q \cong \angle S\) (each support meets the horizontal beam at the same angle)

**Prove:** \(\overline{PR} \cong \overline{QS}\).

### Step 1: Identify the Triangles

Triangle PQR and triangle RSP share the structure. We have two pairs of congruent angles and the included side.

### Step 2: Two-Column Proof

| Statement | Reason |
|-----------|--------|
| 1. \(\angle P \cong \angle R\) | 1. Given |
| 2. \(\overline{PQ} \cong \overline{RS}\) | 2. Given |
| 3. \(\angle Q \cong \angle S\) | 3. Given |
| 4. △PQR ≅ △RSP | 4. ASA (steps 1, 2, 3) |
| 5. \(\overline{PR} \cong \overline{QS}\) | 5. CPCTC |

### Step 3: Interpretation

The engineer can confirm both support beams are equal in length based on the congruent triangles formed with the horizontal beam.

✅ Answer: \(\overline{PR} \cong \overline{QS}\) — the structural supports are equal in length.

